let me share a chunk of what I'm working on because I think there's a subtle bug and rubber-ducking with you usually unsticks me. fair warning: code coming, lots of it. this is the nearest-drivers handler in the rust service.

```rust
#[axum::debug_handler]
async fn nearest_drivers(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Json(req): Json<NearestRequest>,
) -> Result<Json<NearestResponse>, AppError> {
    let pickup = Geometry::Point(req.pickup);
    let radius_m = req.radius_m.unwrap_or(2_000.0);

    let mut tx = state.pool.begin().await?;
    let candidates = sqlx::query_as!(
        DriverRow,
        r#"
        SELECT id as "id!", current_pos as "current_pos!: PgGeography", last_heartbeat
        FROM drivers
        WHERE status = 'available'
          AND ST_DWithin(
              current_pos::geography,
              ST_GeogFromWKB($1)::geography,
              $2
          )
        ORDER BY last_heartbeat DESC
        LIMIT 50
        "#,
        pickup.to_ewkb()?,
        radius_m,
    )
    .fetch_all(&mut *tx)
    .await?;

    let mut results = Vec::with_capacity(candidates.len());
    for cand in candidates {
        let handle = tokio::spawn(score_candidate(cand, req.pickup));
        results.push(handle);
    }

    let mut scored = Vec::with_capacity(results.len());
    for h in results {
        scored.push(h.await??);
    }

    tx.commit().await?;
    Ok(Json(NearestResponse { drivers: scored }))
}
```

works fine in dev. p99 is like 12ms locally with synthetic data. pushed to staging — works fine. ran a synthetic load test of 200 concurrent requests sustained over 10 minutes, and saw two things, both bad:

1) memory grows over time. like, monotonically. not catastrophically — about 8mb per minute of sustained load. but it never returns. after an hour we'd have used 480mb of slack, and after a day we'd be in OOM territory. that's a leak somewhere.

2) occasionally a request takes 3+ seconds when the rest are <50ms. tail is bad. p99 = ~3.2 seconds. and not just bad — bad in a way that suggests a specific resource is contended, not bad in a way that suggests a global slowdown. global slowdown looks like the median rising. this is the median staying the same and the tail spiking. that's contention, not load.

I think I see two problems and I want to walk through them. first one: the `score_candidate` function spawns a tokio task per candidate. each task ends with the result being collected. but I'm spawning N tasks via `tokio::spawn`, then iterating through the JoinHandles in a `for` loop and `.await`ing them serially (`scored.push(h.await??)`). so I'm spawning N tasks but awaiting them serially, which means: yes, the work happens concurrently inside the spawn, BUT my completion order is the spawn order, not the actual completion order. if task #1 takes 2 seconds and tasks #2-#50 each take 30ms, my loop blocks on task #1 for the full 2 seconds. that's not the leak per se but it explains the tail latency: I'm waiting linearly for the slowest task to be at any position in the loop except first. classic head-of-line blocking shape, which I should have spotted faster — head-of-line blocking is one of the things I CLAIM to look out for, and here it is in my own code, and I did not see it on review.

the leak — I think — is something about the JoinHandles I drop on the floor in the early-return error path. let me trace it. when a tx.commit fails, or when ANY .await? returns an Err, the `results` Vec falls out of scope. if any of the tasks haven't completed, dropping their JoinHandles does NOT cancel the tasks. tokio JoinHandles don't auto-cancel on drop. so I have orphaned tasks running to completion in the background, holding onto whatever data they had captured (the candidate, the pickup point, an http client they may have spawned for the grpc call). over many failed requests, that's the slow leak. and not a 'memory disappears' leak — a 'memory is held by tasks that will eventually complete and release it, but slowly, and the next failed request adds more before the previous batch has resolved'. so it's a churning leak rather than a strict leak. but functionally, under sustained load, it accumulates faster than it drains.

the right primitive: `tokio::task::JoinSet`. JoinSet aborts all tasks on drop. and `.join_next()` returns tasks in completion order, not spawn order, which fixes the tail latency too. two birds.

refactoring now. this is, by the way, exactly the kind of thing the post-mortem from the postgres outage was supposed to make me sharper about — not 'be paranoid about postgres' but 'be paranoid about resource lifetimes in async runtimes'. I wrote that post-mortem in month 5, after the 4-hour outage, and I made a section called 'lessons we are extracting' and one of the bullets was 'distributed-system resource lifetimes are easy to mismanage in services that are async by default'. and here I am two months later having made the same shape of mistake in a different runtime. on-brand. the post-mortem documented the lesson and I did not internalize it. the lesson does not become a skill until you have the chance to apply it on a new instance and you see yourself failing the application and you correct it consciously. that's now. this is the moment the abstract becomes the muscle.

the specific change I'm making:

```rust
use tokio::task::JoinSet;

let mut set = JoinSet::new();
for cand in candidates {
    set.spawn(score_candidate(cand, req.pickup));
}
let mut scored = Vec::with_capacity(set.len());
while let Some(res) = set.join_next().await {
    scored.push(res??);
}
```

additional thing I want to add: a timeout. some `score_candidate` calls might be hitting a slow grpc backend. cap the per-task timeout at 250ms with `tokio::time::timeout`, fail soft on individual timeouts (drop that candidate from the result list, log it), keep the request as a whole responsive. that way one slow downstream doesn't wreck everything. structured log per soft-timeout so we can see how often we drop candidates due to slow grpc. expectation is <0.5% under normal load, <2% under burst. anything higher and we have a problem with the grpc service itself, not our timeout.

additional additional thing: I want to add a metric. specifically a counter for 'orphaned-tasks-aborted-on-drop' which JoinSet exposes via its abort callback. that way next time I introduce a similar leak via a different code path, the metric will spike before the memory does. you cannot rely on memory metrics alone for leaks of this shape — by the time the memory metric has spiked, you've already shipped the leak to production. instrument the failure mode, not just the symptom. that's the thing I should have done after the post-mortem and didn't.

deploying this to the load-test environment in 20 min. will report back. and writing 'do not drop JoinHandles on the floor' on the engineering wiki. and writing 'instrument the failure mode, not just the symptom' under it. those are the two takeaways. I am going to print them and put them above my monitor for 90 days because I want them in muscle memory before my next async-resource design.

meta-meta: this is also a thing I want andrés to learn from. when he reviews the joinset PR, I want him to ask 'why JoinSet over JoinHandle Vec'. if he doesn't ask, I will tell him. junior engineers learn from the WHY of the change at least as much as the WHAT. carla, when she's back, will probably also have opinions on the joinset choice because she has been doing more with tokio than I have. fine. she can have opinions. I'd rather her opinions came onto a clean codebase than a leaky one.

and the more I look at this the more I think the real bug is upstream of the code — it's that I keep promising 'I'll just look at it for ten minutes' and then it's two hours and Camila is asking why I'm still at the desk. yesterday she came in at 11:40, didn't say anything, just stood in the doorway with Nube and stared at the back of my head until I closed the laptop. she's getting better at not saying it out loud. I'm getting worse at not requiring her to say it out loud. that ratio is going the wrong direction and I see it.

writing this out is helping more than I expected. the thing about typing the problem is that the typing is slower than the thinking, and the slowness forces a sequencing on the thoughts that the brain doesn't want to do on its own. half the time when I rubber-duck like this the bug reveals itself in the act of describing. the other half it's still a real bug but at least I have an artifact I can paste into the team channel tomorrow. either way it beats spinning in my head at 11pm.

thing I keep noticing — and this is sort of meta but worth recording — is that every time I describe these problems out loud I find a hole in my model. the wkb byte order question, for example, I literally don't have a confident answer to right now: is the SRID prefix on EWKB always little-endian regardless of the wkb byte order flag, or does it follow the wkb endianness? I'd assume the latter but I haven't verified. that's the kind of thing where if I assumed wrong, integration tests pass on dev where everything is little-endian, then explode in some weird big-endian context I'll never see. PostGIS docs are my friend tomorrow.

carla is going to come back from leave and I want to be able to walk her through this in 20 minutes flat — not 'here's everything I tried', but 'here's the decision tree, here's where we landed, here's why, here's the test coverage, here's the open risks'. that's the standard. if I can't do that, I haven't actually solved the problem; I've just spent time on it. there's a difference and daniela has hammered it into me over a year of 1:1s.

